body:
Even though maps and slices are not pointer fields in the generated
code, they are still nullable. Adding an extra check for map/set/list
types fixes the generated Count* methods.

Sample IDL:
```thrift
union Foo{
    1: map<bool,bool> u1
    2: set<bool> u2
    3: list<bool> u3
    4: bool u4
}
```

Generated code before fix:
```go
func (p *Foo) CountSetFieldsFoo() int {
	count := 0
	if p.IsSetU4() {
		count++
	}
	return count
}
```

After fix:
```go
func (p *Foo) CountSetFieldsFoo() int {
	count := 0
	if p.IsSetU1() {
		count++
	}
	if p.IsSetU2() {
		count++
	}
	if p.IsSetU3() {
		count++
	}
	if p.IsSetU4() {
		count++
	}
	return count
}
```

Fixes THRIFT-3703.

Client: rs

**Overview**

* Replaces single-threaded synchronous server with synchronous threadpool server
* Removes refcounting (simplifies reasoning about thread-safety - i.e. when developing server)
* Reworked types to allow for single-instance ownership and remove refcounting
* Removed `Box` in the user-visible API

**Rationale**

The original version of the library supported only single-threaded operation. To encode the idea that a `Transport` could be shared by a `InputProtocol` and an `OutputProtocol` I used reference-counting via `Rc` in the user-visible API. When I implemented the threaded server I would have had to change all instances of `Rc` to `Arc` for thread-safety. This would incur a large runtime cost (each access of a `*Protocol`, many hundreds while serializing and deserializing messages) for no good reason: after all, while two threads may read/write from the same socket or channel concurrently, only one thread would ever be reading and another thread the writing.

Using inspiration from [Tokio](https://tokio.rs) I pushed the concept of shared ownership *into* a new low-level construct - `TIoChannel`, and allowed it to be `split()` into a readable and writable type, each of which could be owned by upper layers. This allowed me to remove all reference counting and explicit boxing in the user-visible API and allowed for a straightforward implementation of a threaded server. It also made the library easier to use and simplified test code.

Consider the two code samples below:

*Original:*

```rust
use std::cell::RefCell;
use std::rc::Rc;
use thrift::protocol::{TBinaryInputProtocol, TInputProtocol};
use thrift::transport::{TTcpTransport, TTransport};

// create the I/O channel
let mut transport = TTcpTransport::new();
transport.open("127.0.0.1:9090").unwrap();
let transport = Rc::new(RefCell::new(Box::new(transport) as Box<TTransport>));

// create the protocol to decode bytes into types
let mut protocol = TBinaryInputProtocol::new(transport.clone(), true);

// read types from the wire
let field_identifier = protocol.read_field_begin().unwrap();
let field_contents = protocol.read_string().unwrap();
let field_end = protocol.read_field_end().unwrap();
```
`transport` has to be explicitly ref-counted, boxed and cloned into the `protocol`.

*Updated:*

```rust
use thrift::protocol::{TBinaryInputProtocol, TInputProtocol};
use thrift::transport::TTcpChannel;

// create the I/O channel
let mut transport = TTcpChannel::new();
transport.open("127.0.0.1:9090").unwrap();

// create the protocol to decode bytes into types
let mut protocol = TBinaryInputProtocol::new(transport, true);

// read types from the wire
let field_identifier = protocol.read_field_begin().unwrap();
let field_contents = protocol.read_string().unwrap();
let field_end = protocol.read_field_end().unwrap();
```
`transport` can be used directly, without any additional wrapping.

**Testing**

* C++ code compiles cleanly without warnings
* All cross-tests pass
* All library, tutorial, test and cross-test code pass clippy lint checks

**Additional Notes**

As requested in the [THRIFT-4176](https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/THRIFT-4176) JIRA discussion I've *replaced* the existing single-threaded, synchronous server with a fixed-size threadpool-based server.
